3","1345":"1345","1398":"1398","1442":"1442","1440":"1440","1362":"1362","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","1470":"1470","Carlisle, Cumberland, England":"Carlisle, Cumberland, England","Cumberland, England, United Kingdom":"Cumberland, Cumberland, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England, United Kingdom":"England","Cumberland, England":"Cumberland, England"},"en":{"1345–1440":"1345–1440","1340–1403":"1340–1403","1362–1442":"1362–1442","1398–1470":"1398–1470","1403":"1403","1345":"1345","1398":"1398","1442":"1442","1440":"1440","1362":"1362","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","1470":"1470","Carlisle, Cumberland, England":"Carlisle, Cumberland, England","Cumberland, England, United Kingdom":"Cumberland, Cumberland, England, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"England","Cumberland, England":"Cumberland, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Strickland","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): habitational name from Great and Little Strickland (Westmorland) or Strickland Ketel and Strickland Roger (also Westmorland). The placenames derive from Old English <i>stīrc</i> ‘stirk, young bullock or heifer’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’."],"variants":[{"name":"Stricklen","meanings":["English: variant of   Strickland  ."]},{"name":"Stricklan","meanings":["English: variant of   Strickland  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":37,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Strickland was born in 1345, in England. She had at least 2 daughters with John Derwentwater. She died in 1440, in Cumberland, England, at the age of 95, and was buried in Carlisle, Cumberland, England."},"et":{"1345–1440":"1345–1440","1340–1403":"1340–1403","1362–1442":"1362–1442","1398–1470":"1398–1470","1403":"1403","1345":"1345","1398":"1398","1442":"1442","1440":"1440","1362":"1362","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","1470":"1470","Carlisle, Cumberland, England":"Carlisle, Cumberland, England","Cumberland, England, United Kingdom":"Cumberland, Cumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"England","Cumberland, England":"Cumberland, England"},"fi":{"1345–1440":"1345–1440","1340–1403":"1340–1403","1362–1442":"1362–1442","1398–1470":"1398–1470","1403":"1403","1345":"1345","1398":"1398","1442":"1442","1440":"1440","1362":"1362","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","1470":"1470","Carlisle, Cumberland, England":"Carlisle, Cumberland, England","Cumberland, England, United Kingdom":"Cumberland, Cumberland, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England, United Kingdom":"England","Cumberland, England":"Cumberland, England"},"fr":{"1345–1440":"1345–1440","1340–1403":"1340–1403","1362–1442":"1362–1442","1398–1470":"1398–1470","1403":"1403","1345":"1345","1398":"1398","1442":"1442","1440":"1440","1362":"1362","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","1470":"1470","Carlisle, Cumberland, England":"Carlisle, Cumberland, Angleterre","Cumberland, England, United Kingdom":"Cumberland, Cumberland, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","England, United Kingdom":"Angleterre","Cumberland, England":"Cumberland, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Margaret Strickland est née en 1345, à Angleterre. Elle a eu au moins 2 filles avec John Derwentwater. Elle est décédée en 1440, à Cumberland, Angleterre, à l’âge de 95 ans